english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of Hoeamsa Temple on Cheonbosan Mountain
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "The abbot Yunjeol of Hoeamsa Temple once spoke to me, saying: \"Now that Boje has passed away and the monks have inscribed his epitaph upon stone, the founding of this temple too should be recorded in full detail, that it might illuminate Boje's unwavering dedication to this place through endless ages. It is to you alone that I entrust this task—I beseech you, do not refuse.\" I replied, \"Very well.\" Not long after, his disciple Gakjeon came again and said: \"My master has departed, and we disciples have scattered to the four corners. Whether this temple shall endure as it once was remains uncertain. Alas, how sorrowful! My master's way is not something the world may judge as light or heavy. Yet whether the temple shall flourish or decline rests with those who come after—with whether we disciples can sustain it. This too lies beyond our foresight. Alas, how sorrowful! Where my master laid the foundation here, the very places he marked and where he stood remain unchanged as before. Yet his voice and presence have faded into the distance. Where my master expounded the dharma, the forms of his prayers and the vigor of his teaching remain as they were. Yet his authority and commands have grown silent. The halls stand empty, the incense grows sparse, and the moonlit river landscape dissolves into wild mist. And yet—Buddha-nature dwells in the heart, and we must fear what the coming generation may achieve. How can we know that there shall not arise one who surpasses the blue of yesterday's sky? This is wherein we find our consolation. But I fear that future people may not know this history. They may call it a new construction and tear it down. Then the devoted works of Boje's disciples—all their strenuous efforts to create this beauty—would be erased and forgotten forever. This grieves me deeply. Therefore I have brought this record, hoping only that you, Master, would set it down in writing.\" \n\nLet me now describe what I have examined: The Guangming Hall stands five bays facing south. Behind it is the Dharma Hall, also five bays. Behind that lies the Reliquary Hall of a single bay, and behind that the Main Hall of three bays. East and west of the Main Hall stand two abbot's quarters, each of three pillars. East of the eastern quarters lies the Arhat Hall of three bays, and west of the western quarters the Great Sutra Repository of three bays. The meditation quarters face west before the eastern abbot's quarters, while the attendant's quarters face east before the western ones. West of the Dharma Hall stands the Patriarch's Hall, with the head monk's quarters further west. East of the Dharma Hall lies the portrait hall, with the recording monk's quarters beyond. All face south. South of the portrait hall, facing west, stands the incense-keeping quarters. South of the Patriarch's Hall, facing east, lies the sutra-keeper's quarters. Southeast of the Guangming Hall spreads the sandalwood grove, where the eastern assembly hall faces west and the western assembly hall faces east. East of the eastern assembly hall the eastern work quarters face west, and west of the western assembly hall the western work quarters face east. A covered corridor of three bays connects the western meditation hall. The main gate of the Guangming Hall spans three bays, with an eastern corridor of six bays connecting to the south of the eastern guest hall. West of the gate stands the joyous assembly quarters of seven bays, which bend northward for another seven bays as the eastern quarters. Five bays east of the main gate, facing west, form the eastern guest hall. Five bays to its west, facing east, form the western guest hall. South of the joyous assembly quarters stands the Guanyin Hall. Five bays to its west, facing east, form the bathhouse. East of the assistant director's quarters lies the Amitabha Hall. The director's quarters, five bays facing south, has the storehouse to its east. To the south lies a heart corridor of seven bays connecting to the Amitabha Hall. To the north stands a sauce storehouse of fourteen bays. East of the storehouse extends eleven bays with the storehouse gate, leading east four bays from the tower, then bending north six bays, then west for two bays, leaving the western side open. Directly southeast of the main gate rises the bell tower of three bays. South of the tower, five bays form the sand chamber. Facing east from the tower's west stands the reception hall. The guest-master's quarters extends northeast from the bell tower. South of the reception hall, facing east, stands the hall for the aged. East of the guest-master's quarters, facing west, lies the head cook's quarters. Bending east from here, seven bays form the fragrant accumulation hall. East of this hall and south of the storehouse stand three bays of the gardener's quarters, facing west. South of the fragrant accumulation hall, four bays form the stable. In all, there are two hundred sixty-two structures. Of the Buddha statues, seven reach fifteen feet in height, while the Guanyin image, ten feet tall, was sponsored by Gakjeon. Their grandeur, magnificence, and beauty surpass all in the eastern lands. Those who travel the rivers and lakes say that even in the Middle Kingdom, one would not often find their equal—and this is no exaggeration.\n\nI have never favored Buddhist teachings, yet because the late king once took reverence for them, I have maintained my respect. Moreover, having received the command to compose this record, I investigated the great master's entire life in detail and came to understand that he was no ordinary man. The creation of Buddha images and pagodas holds no true merit in themselves; the great master's way transcends such considerations. Since the abbot's request and Gakjeon's earnest devotion were not matters to be dismissed lightly, I inquired about when the work began and ended, and they named the specific months and years. I then said: \"Remarkable! How smoothly it all came to pass. Without the great master's way to move the hearts of capable people, and without the talents of his disciples for such undertakings, how could this have been achieved? And yet, to establish a foundation and transmit a lineage for those who come after is the work of a true gentleman. But for one to ignore what lies ahead, to disregard the measure of the vessel, and to pursue one's desires to the utmost extravagance—this a gentleman would find contemptible. Nevertheless, the great master possessed foresight, and Boje's vow was sacred. How could we doubt that this dharma place shall flourish ever more and never decline? For these reasons, I undertake this record with joy.\"\n"
